Number = {{1}},
Pages = {{26-30}},
Month = {{FEB}},
Abstract = {{Measurements of concentrations of easily extractable soil nitrogen (N)
   were carried out on samples collected at the Heron Wood Reserve,
   Scotland, concurrently with investigations of N associated with total
   microbial biomass and the abundances of bacteria, fungi, and
   invertebrates. Soil biota at the studied site appeared to be limited by
   N. There was a remarkable difference between the ambient (i.e., easily
   extractable N) and biomass nitrogen. The abundance data of bacteria,
   protozoa and nematodes significantly negatively correlated with ambient
   N but showed positive correlations with the total microbial N content.
   There were, however, remarkable differences between the correlation
   patterns exhibited by the fungal and the bacterial pathways, as fungi
   did not show any correlations with chemical variables. These differences
   should be taken into account whilst interpreting biological interactions
   both at this important site and elsewhere.}},
